explanation: int32 (typedef): Needed to understand the type of the local variable Status and how it is passed/cast to callees (ensures casting or definition does not hide pointer/aliasing that could be treated as a modified parameter). OS_API_Init (prototype): To confirm its return type and parameter list (even though it is called without arguments here) and to ensure it is not a macro that could expand to code that modifies any parameter of OS_Application_Startup. OS_SUCCESS (macro/enum): To evaluate the conditional and confirm no side effects (some macros can expand to expressions with assignments). BSP_DEBUG (macro or function definition): BSP_DEBUG is used with Status as an argument; if BSP_DEBUG is a macro it could expand to code that modifies its argument(s) (which would violate the rule if it modified a parameter). The exact macro or function implementation is required to determine whether any parameter object is modified. OS_ApplicationExit (prototype): Needed to know its parameter types (by-value vs pointer) and whether it is actually a macro that might modify its argument expression. If it accepts a pointer or is a macro manipulating its argument, that could mean the caller passes a parameter that is subsequently modified; the prototype/definition rules this out.
